{"title_page": "Orit Wolf", "text_new": "{{format|date=August 2017}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name                = Orit Wolf\n| background          = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| image               = ORIT WOLF1.jpg\n| image_size          = \n| alt                 = \n| caption             = \n| birth_name          = \n| alias               = \n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1974|10|8}}\n| birth_place         = [[Tel Aviv]]\n| origin              =\n| death_date          = <!-- {{death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date 1st) -->\n| death_place         = \n| genre               = \n| occupation          = <nowiki>[[Pianist and Innovation Mentor] </nowiki>\n| instrument          = \n| years_active        = <!-- YYYY\u2013YYYY (or \u2013present) -->\n| label               = \n| associated_acts     = \n| website             = {{URL|www.oritwolf.com}}\n}}\n'''Orit Wolf''' (Ph.D) ({{lang-he|\u05d0\u05d5\u05e8\u05d9\u05ea \u05d5\u05d5\u05dc\u05e3}}, born 1974 in [[Tel Aviv]]) is an [[Israelis|Israeli]] [[pianist]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/jpost/access/62539296.html?dids=62539296:62539296&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&date=Jul+04%2C+1995&author=Ury+Eppstein%3B+Michael+Ajzenstadt&pub=Jerusalem+Post&desc=Pianist+Orit+Wolf+displays+sensitivity%2C+refinement+in+debut&pqatl=google|title=Pianist Orit Wolf displays sensitivity, refinement in debut|last=Eppstein|first=Ury|author2=Michael Ajzenstadt|date=July 4, 1995|work=[[Jerusalem Post]]|page=7|accessdate=7 May 2011}}</ref> and [[composer]]. Currently holds a lecturer position at the [[Royal Academy of Music]], London. She is also a guest lecturer and a mentor on the area of [[Innovation]], [[Creativity]] and [[Leadership]].\n\n==Education==\nStarted at the age of six, Orit Wolf was studying with [[Hanna Shalgi]]. At the age of 16 she graduated from [[Thelma Yelin]] High School for the Arts and studied with Prof. [[Alexander Volkov (pianist)|Alexander Volkov]], she  began her academic studies at the [[Tel Aviv University]] under the direction of [[Arie Vardi]]. She also studied music composition and improvisation with [[Andre Hajdu]] while attending masterclasses given by [[Leon Fleisher]], [[Claude Frank]], [[Menahem Pressler|Menachem Pressle]]<nowiki/>r, [[Gyorge Shebok]], [[Gilbert Kalish]] and [[Peter Serkin]].\n\nIn 1991, Wolf attended the [[Boston University Tanglewood Institute]] and then received a full Dean's scholarship to [[Boston University]]. She graduated from Boston University [[Summa Cum Laude]] in piano performance under Prof. [[Benjamin Pasternack]] and Composer [[Lukas Foss]].\n\nWolf received a post-graduate degree (DipRAM) and her Masters (M.Mus) from the [[Royal Academy of Music]] in 1998 under the direction of [[Christopher Elton]]. She was also studying with [[Maria Curcio]].\n\nIn 2007, Wolf earned a [[Ph.D]] under the President Scholaships from [[Bar-Ilan University]] in [[Musicology]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jpost.com/LandedPages/PrintArticle.aspx?id=214323|title=Israel News - Jpost.com Israel|website=www.jpost.com}}</ref> Her thesis title was \"Beethoven as Heard by the Romantics: A Study of Romantic Style Cadenzas Composed to [[Piano Concerto No. 4 (Beethoven)|Beethoven's Fourth Piano Concerto\"]].<ref>http://www.oritwolf.com/music/?page_id=439</ref>\n\n==Performances and distinctions==\nAt the age of 11, she was invited to perform in [[Germany]] and [[Belgium]] on behalf of the [[Israel Broadcasting Authority]]. At the age of 14, she recorded for \"Kol Ha-Musica\", the Israeli Classical Radio Music Station (IBO), on various performances which includes her own compositions.\n\nWolf has performed as a soloist and with various orchestras including the [[Israel Chamber Orchestra]], [[Jerusalem Symphony Orchestra]], [[Rishon LeZion#Culture|Rishon LeZion Symphony]], [[Braslaw Philharmonic]], [[Royal Academy Symphony Orchestra]] and [[English Chamber Orchestra|the English Chamber Orchestra]]. She has played at the [[Tanglewood Music Festival]] and [[Israel Festival]] ([[Israel]]), East West Festival (Holland) and the [[Upper Galilee Music Festival]]. She has played in prestigious concert halls such as the [[Wigmore Hall]], St. Matrin Hall (London), Symphony Hall (Boston), The [[Concertgebouw]] (Amsterdam) and the [[Alte Oper]] (Frankfurt).\n\nWolf has collaborated with numerous international artists and ensembles such as [[St. Lawrence String Quartet|St. Lawerence Quartet]], [[\u05e8\u05d1\u05d9\u05e2\u05d9\u05d9\u05ea \u05d0\u05d1\u05d9\u05d1|Aviv Quartet]], [[Joanna MacGregor|Joanna McGreggor]], [[Nobuko Imai]], [[\u05e9\u05de\u05d7\u05d4 \u05d7\u05dc\u05d3|Simca Heled]], David D'or,  Erez Ofer, [[Sergei Krylov (violinist)|Sergei Krylov]], [[Hagai Shaham]], Hillel Zori and [[Christine Brewer]]. She records regularly for many radio stations including the [[BBC]], [[CBS]], [[CBC Radio|CBC]], [[Radio IBO|IBO]], [[WGBH (FM)|WGBH]], [[NRK]] and [[BBC London 94.9|GLR]].\n\nIn 2007 Wolf released a CD of recordings titled ''Impulse''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oritwolf.com/music/?page_id=136|title=Audio : Orit Wolf \u2013 Concert Pianist -- \u05d0\u05d5\u05e8\u05d9\u05ea \u05d5\u05d5\u05dc\u05e3 \u2013 \u05e4\u05e1\u05e0\u05ea\u05e8\u05e0\u05d9\u05ea|first=Orit|last=Wolf|website=www.oritwolf.com}}</ref>\n\nSince 2007 Wolf conducts her own Concert Lecture Series. She has founded over 8 series with thousands of subscribers. Her home base is the [[Tel Aviv Museum of Art]] where she holds two main concert series named: ''On a Personal Note''. She hosts and performs live with acclaimed international guest artists as well as conversing with them freely on stage. She performs over 90 concerts a year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oritwolf.com/music/?page_id=120|title=Concert Dates : Orit Wolf \u2013 Concert Pianist -- \u05d0\u05d5\u05e8\u05d9\u05ea \u05d5\u05d5\u05dc\u05e3 \u2013 \u05e4\u05e1\u05e0\u05ea\u05e8\u05e0\u05d9\u05ea|first=Orit|last=Wolf|website=www.oritwolf.com}}</ref> She is also an artisitc director of concert series in Israel Museum, Jerusalem Theatre, Haifa Museum, Ashdod, Nahariya, Kfar Yona, Raanana and Kfar Shmaryu. She fulfils her vision to bring Classical Music into wide variety of audiences and creates interdiscplinary performances where different international artists meet, perform and converse. She is also welknown by her Mesh Ups collaborations, transcriptions and creations with classical music versus popular music. In 2019 She received the Rozenblum Prize for her distinctive contribution to the music world by the Tel Aviv Municipality.  This prize is in addition to her Kahn Award for the arts ( Boston), ARAM ( London), East & West Artist International ( NY), America Israel Cultural Founation ( IL) and many more. \n\nRecently Wolf was invited to give a TED talk on \"Play the Keynote of your Life\"- brining Music, Leaderhip and Innovation into action and collaboration. \n\nWolf is also a business consultant in the area of innovative thinking and creative marketing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://osloartistformidling.no/Foredragsholdere/Vaare-foredragsholdere/Orit-Wolf|title=Orit Wolf|publisher=}}{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> in 2010 [[TheMarker|The Marker]] Magazine has chosen her as one of the hundred most influential people of the year. She is consider one of the top guest lectures on the area of [[Music]], [[Leadership]] and [[Creativity techniques|Creativity]].<ref>http://oritwolf.com/business/en/?page_id=23</ref>\n\n== Compositions ==\n* ''Associations from Liszt'' \u2013 Piano version 1990 (Download score in PDF)<ref>http://www.oritwolf.com/music/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/Associations-from-Liszt-Pno.pdf</ref> \n* ''Memories from a temple'' \u2013 (Solo Piano) 1994 (Download score in PDF)<ref>http://www.oritwolf.com/music/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/Memories-from-a-Temple.pdf</ref>  \n* ''Prelude and Fugue'' \u2013 (Solo Piano) 1995 \n* ''Nostalgia from Grandfather'' \u2013 (Solo Piano-Free Improvisation) 1997\n* ''Kol Nidrei'' \u2013 (Solo Piano-Free Improvisation) 2000  \n* ''Association from Liszt'' \u2013 for Viola, Clarinet and Piano, 2001\n* Ben Haim/Orit Wolf: ''Lullaby'' \u2013 Transcription for Violin, Clarinet and Piano, 2002 \n* ''Human\u2019s Love'' \u2013 Romanza for Violin and Piano, 2003, Download score in PDF: 1<ref>http://www.oritwolf.com/music/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/Romanza-for-Violin-and-Piano.pdf</ref> / and 2<ref>http://www.oritwolf.com/music/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/Romanza-Vln.pdf</ref>\n* ''Kadenza'' for Mozart\u2019s Piano Concerto No. 23 K. 488, 2005 (Download score in PDF<ref>http://www.oritwolf.com/music/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/Cadenza-from-Mozart-Concerto.pdf</ref>\n* ''White, Light and Argaman'' \u2013 for Symphony Orchestra, 2006 (Premiered by the Rishon Lezziyon Symphony Orchestra, November 2006) (Download score in PDF<ref>http://www.oritwolf.com/music/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/Light-White-and-Argaman.pdf</ref>\n* ''Introspection'' \u2013 for Violin and Piano, 2007  ''Longings ''(Solo Piano), 2007\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wolf, Orit}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century classical composers]]\n[[Category:21st-century classical composers]]\n[[Category:20th-century pianists]]\n[[Category:21st-century pianists]]\n[[Category:Israeli composers]]\n[[Category:Israeli pianists]]\n[[Category:Israeli businesspeople]]\n[[Category:People from Tel Aviv]]\n[[Category:Bar-Ilan University faculty]]\n[[Category:Female classical composers]]\n[[Category:20th-century women musicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century women musicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{format|date=August 2017}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name                = Orit Wolf\n| background          = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| image               = ORIT WOLF1.jpg\n| image_size          = \n| alt                 = \n| caption             = \n| birth_name          = \n| alias               = \n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1974|10|8}}\n| birth_place         = [[Tel Aviv]]\n| origin              =\n| death_date          = <!-- {{death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date 1st) -->\n| death_place         = \n| genre               = \n| occupation          = <nowiki>[[Pianist and Innovation Mentor] </nowiki>\n| instrument          = \n| years_active        = <!-- YYYY\u2013YYYY (or \u2013present) -->\n| label               = \n| associated_acts     = \n| website             = {{URL|www.oritwolf.com}}\n}}\n'''Orit Wolf''' (Ph.D) ({{lang-he|\u05d0\u05d5\u05e8\u05d9\u05ea \u05d5\u05d5\u05dc\u05e3}}, born 1974 in [[Tel Aviv]]) is an [[Israelis|Israeli]] [[pianist]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/jpost/access/62539296.html?dids=62539296:62539296&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&date=Jul+04%2C+1995&author=Ury+Eppstein%3B+Michael+Ajzenstadt&pub=Jerusalem+Post&desc=Pianist+Orit+Wolf+displays+sensitivity%2C+refinement+in+debut&pqatl=google|title=Pianist Orit Wolf displays sensitivity, refinement in debut|last=Eppstein|first=Ury|author2=Michael Ajzenstadt|date=July 4, 1995|work=[[Jerusalem Post]]|page=7|accessdate=7 May 2011}}</ref> and [[composer]]. Currently holds a lecturer position at the [[Royal Academy of Music]], London. She is also a guest lecturer and a mentor on the area of [[Innovation]], [[Creativity]] and [[Leadership]].\n\n==Education==\nStarted at the age of six, Orit Wolf was studying with [[Hanna Shalgi]]. At the age of 16 she graduated from [[Thelma Yelin]] High School for the Arts and studied with Prof. [[Alexander Volkov (pianist)|Alexander Volkov]], she  began her academic studies at the [[Tel Aviv University]] under the direction of [[Arie Vardi]]. She also studied music composition and improvisation with [[Andre Hajdu]] while attending masterclasses given by [[Leon Fleisher]], [[Claude Frank]], [[Menahem Pressler|Menachem Pressle]]<nowiki/>r, [[Gyorge Shebok]], [[Gilbert Kalish]] and [[Peter Serkin]].\n\nIn 1991, Wolf attended the [[Boston University Tanglewood Institute]] and then received a full Dean's scholarship to [[Boston University]]. She graduated from Boston University [[Summa Cum Laude]] in piano performance under Prof. [[Benjamin Pasternack]] and Composer [[Lukas Foss]].\n\nWolf received a post-graduate degree (DipRAM) and her Masters (M.Mus) from the [[Royal Academy of Music]] in 1998 under the direction of [[Christopher Elton]]. She was also studying with [[Maria Curcio]].\n\nIn 2007, Wolf earned a [[Ph.D]] under the President Scholaships from [[Bar-Ilan University]] in [[Musicology]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jpost.com/LandedPages/PrintArticle.aspx?id=214323|title=Israel News - Jpost.com Israel|website=www.jpost.com}}</ref> Her thesis title was \"Beethoven as Heard by the Romantics: A Study of Romantic Style Cadenzas Composed to [[Piano Concerto No. 4 (Beethoven)|Beethoven's Fourth Piano Concerto\"]].<ref>http://www.oritwolf.com/music/?page_id=439</ref>\n\n==Performances==\nAt the age of 11, she was invited to perform in [[Germany]] and [[Belgium]] on behalf of the [[Israel Broadcasting Authority]]. At the age of 14, she recorded for \"Kol Ha-Musica\", the Israeli Classical Radio Music Station (IBO), on various performances which includes her own compositions.\n\nWolf has performed as a soloist and with various orchestras including the [[Israel Chamber Orchestra]], [[Jerusalem Symphony Orchestra]], [[Rishon LeZion#Culture|Rishon LeZion Symphony]], [[Braslaw Philharmonic]], [[Royal Academy Symphony Orchestra]] and [[English Chamber Orchestra|the English Chamber Orchestra]]. She has played at the [[Tanglewood Music Festival]] and [[Israel Festival]] ([[Israel]]), East West Festival (Holland) and the [[Upper Galilee Music Festival]]. She has played in prestigious concert halls such as the [[Wigmore Hall]], St. Matrin Hall (London), Symphony Hall (Boston), The [[Concertgebouw]] (Amsterdam) and the [[Alte Oper]] (Frankfurt).\n\nWolf has collaborated with numerous international artists and ensembles such as [[St. Lawrence String Quartet|St. Lawerence Quartet]], [[\u05e8\u05d1\u05d9\u05e2\u05d9\u05d9\u05ea \u05d0\u05d1\u05d9\u05d1|Aviv Quartet]], [[Joanna MacGregor|Joanna McGreggor]], [[Nobuko Imai]], [[\u05e9\u05de\u05d7\u05d4 \u05d7\u05dc\u05d3|Simca Heled]], Erez Ofer, [[Sergei Krylov (violinist)|Sergei Krylov]], [[Hagai Shaham]], Hillel Zori and [[Christine Brewer]]. She records regularly for many radio stations including the [[BBC]], [[CBS]], [[CBC Radio|CBC]], [[Radio IBO|IBO]], [[WGBH (FM)|WGBH]], [[NRK]] and [[BBC London 94.9|GLR]].\n\nIn 2007 Wolf released a CD of recordings titled ''Impulse''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oritwolf.com/music/?page_id=136|title=Audio : Orit Wolf \u2013 Concert Pianist -- \u05d0\u05d5\u05e8\u05d9\u05ea \u05d5\u05d5\u05dc\u05e3 \u2013 \u05e4\u05e1\u05e0\u05ea\u05e8\u05e0\u05d9\u05ea|first=Orit|last=Wolf|website=www.oritwolf.com}}</ref>\n\nSince 2007 Wolf conducts her own Concert Lecture Series. She has founded over 8 series with thousands of subscribers. Her home base is the [[Tel Aviv Museum of Art]] where she holds two main concert series named: ''On a Personal Note''. She hosts and performs live with acclaimed international guest artists as well as conversing with them freely on stage. She performs over 90 concerts a year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oritwolf.com/music/?page_id=120|title=Concert Dates : Orit Wolf \u2013 Concert Pianist -- \u05d0\u05d5\u05e8\u05d9\u05ea \u05d5\u05d5\u05dc\u05e3 \u2013 \u05e4\u05e1\u05e0\u05ea\u05e8\u05e0\u05d9\u05ea|first=Orit|last=Wolf|website=www.oritwolf.com}}</ref>\n\nWolf is also a business consultant in the area of innovative thinking and creative marketing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://osloartistformidling.no/Foredragsholdere/Vaare-foredragsholdere/Orit-Wolf|title=Orit Wolf|publisher=}}{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> in 2010 [[TheMarker|The Marker]] Magazine has chosen her as one of the hundred most influential people of the year. She is consider one of the top guest lectures on the area of [[Music]], [[Leadership]] and [[Creativity techniques|Creativity]].<ref>http://oritwolf.com/business/en/?page_id=23</ref>\n\n== Compositions ==\n* ''Associations from Liszt'' \u2013 Piano version 1990 (Download score in PDF)<ref>http://www.oritwolf.com/music/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/Associations-from-Liszt-Pno.pdf</ref> \n* ''Memories from a temple'' \u2013 (Solo Piano) 1994 (Download score in PDF)<ref>http://www.oritwolf.com/music/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/Memories-from-a-Temple.pdf</ref>  \n* ''Prelude and Fugue'' \u2013 (Solo Piano) 1995 \n* ''Nostalgia from Grandfather'' \u2013 (Solo Piano-Free Improvisation) 1997\n* ''Kol Nidrei'' \u2013 (Solo Piano-Free Improvisation) 2000  \n* ''Association from Liszt'' \u2013 for Viola, Clarinet and Piano, 2001\n* Ben Haim/Orit Wolf: ''Lullaby'' \u2013 Transcription for Violin, Clarinet and Piano, 2002 \n* ''Human\u2019s Love'' \u2013 Romanza for Violin and Piano, 2003, Download score in PDF: 1<ref>http://www.oritwolf.com/music/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/Romanza-for-Violin-and-Piano.pdf</ref> / and 2<ref>http://www.oritwolf.com/music/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/Romanza-Vln.pdf</ref>\n* ''Kadenza'' for Mozart\u2019s Piano Concerto No. 23 K. 488, 2005 (Download score in PDF<ref>http://www.oritwolf.com/music/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/Cadenza-from-Mozart-Concerto.pdf</ref>\n* ''White, Light and Argaman'' \u2013 for Symphony Orchestra, 2006 (Premiered by the Rishon Lezziyon Symphony Orchestra, November 2006) (Download score in PDF<ref>http://www.oritwolf.com/music/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/Light-White-and-Argaman.pdf</ref>\n* ''Introspection'' \u2013 for Violin and Piano, 2007  ''Longings ''(Solo Piano), 2007\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wolf, Orit}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century classical composers]]\n[[Category:21st-century classical composers]]\n[[Category:20th-century pianists]]\n[[Category:21st-century pianists]]\n[[Category:Israeli composers]]\n[[Category:Israeli pianists]]\n[[Category:Israeli businesspeople]]\n[[Category:People from Tel Aviv]]\n[[Category:Bar-Ilan University faculty]]\n[[Category:Female classical composers]]\n[[Category:20th-century women musicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century women musicians]]\n", "name_user": "Oritwolf", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePerformances", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orit_Wolf"}
{"title_page": "Gaelic games county colours", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{More citations needed|date=April 2011}}\n[[File:Croke Park fans on the hill.jpg|thumb|right|Fans of [[Tyrone GAA|Tyrone]] (red and white) and [[Meath GAA|Meath]] (green and yellow) on [[Hill 16]] in [[Croke Park]] watching the teams' [[All-Ireland Senior Football Championship 2007#AIQF|2007 All-Ireland football quarterfinal]].]]\nThe '''county colours''' of an [[Counties of Ireland|Irish county]] are the colours of the kit worn by [[GAA county|that county's representative team]] in the inter-county competitions of the [[Gaelic Athletic Association]] (GAA), the most important of which are the [[All-Ireland Senior Football Championship]] and the [[All-Ireland Senior Hurling Championship]].  Fans attending matches often wear replica jerseys, and wave [[flag]]s and [[banner]]s in the county colours.  In the build-up to a major match, flags and [[Bunting (textile)|bunting]] are flown or hung from cars, buildings, telegraph poles, and other fixtures across the county, especially in those regions where GAA support is strong.\n\nWhere a county's jersey is multi-coloured, these are the county colours.  Where the jersey is a single colour, the colour of the shorts is also included.  Shorts were always white until [[Down GAA|Down]] wore black shorts in the [[1968 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship Final|1968 football final]] against [[Kerry GAA|Kerry]], for better contrast in the black-and-white RT\u00c9 telecast.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Keogh |first1=Peter |title=Keogh's Corner: Qualifier draw |url=https://www.pressreader.com/ireland/wicklow-people/20090715/282647503515373 |accessdate=21 August 2019 |work=Wicklow People |via=PressReader.com |date=15 July 2009 |page=62}}</ref> Despite colour telecasts' 1971 arrival,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Boyd |first1=Brian |title=Eurovision in Dublin, 1971: hotpants, 'women\u2019s lib' and boycotts |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/culture/tv-radio-web/eurovision-in-dublin-1971-hotpants-women-s-lib-and-boycotts-1.3491717 |accessdate=21 August 2019 |work=The Irish Times |date=12 May 2018 |language=en}}</ref> other counties switched from white shorts, such as [[Dublin GAA|Dublin]]'s now familiar navy blue.\n\nIn the early years of the All-Ireland championships, each county was formally represented by the club which won its county championship;  players from other clubs within the county were soon added to reinforce the squad, and gradually from 1900 county committees took over the selection of the team. At that date most inter-county teams still wore the kit of the champion club, but by 1910 some counties had adopted a standard strip.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Cronin |first1=Mike |last2=Duncan |first2=Mark |last3=Rouse |first3=Paul |title=The GAA : county by county |date=2011 |publisher=Collins Press |location=Cork |isbn=9781848891289 |pages=6}}</ref> The 1913 [[GAA Congress]] passed a motion proposed by [[P. D. Mehigan]] and seconded by [[Harry Boland]], \"That a distinctive county colour be compulsory for inter-county, inter-provincial and All-Ireland contests, such colours to be approved of by the Provincial Councils concerned and registered with Central Council.\"<ref>{{cite book |last1=Maher |first1=Jim |title=Harry Boland |date=1998 |publisher=Mercier Press |isbn=9781856352369 |page=18 |language=en}}; {{cite web |title=Agenda for 1913 Congress |url=http://www.gaa.ie/centenary/administrative-docs/agenda-f/ |website=Centenary |publisher=GAA |accessdate=9 August 2018 |page=2, Motion 15 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Flags and arms==\n[[File:Dublin Castle Upper Yard county flags.jpg|thumb|Flags with counties' colours and [[List of Irish counties' coats of arms|coats of arms]] flying in the Upper Yard at [[Dublin Castle]]]]\nIn the latter half of the 20th century, the [[county council#Ireland|county council]]s of most counties [[List of Irish counties' coats of arms|designed coats of arms]] for registration with the [[Chief Herald of Ireland]]. Before then, the arms of the [[county town]] often served as arms for the county. The council arms often include the county colours established by the GAA team; examples include [[County Clare|Clare]]<ref>{{cite web |title=What is Clare County Council's Coat of Arms? |url=http://www.clarelibrary.ie/eolas/coclare/history/faqs/council_crest.htm |website=Clare History |publisher=Clare Library |accessdate=14 May 2019}}</ref> and [[County Laois|Laois]].<ref>{{cite web |title=History of the Council \u00bb Coat of Arms |url=https://laois.ie/about-the-council/history-of-the-council/coat-of-arms/ |publisher=Laois County Council |accessdate=14 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nThere are no official county flags; flags with the GAA county colours serve as de facto county flags.  There are no standardised formats for these, except [[Kildare GAA|Kildare]] whose flag, like their kit, is all-white. Typically, flags are formed as vertical bicolours or tricolours, with the major colour nearest the hoist. Horizontal stripes are also found. This is common in [[County Offaly]], where vertical county colours might be mistaken for the [[flag of Ireland]]; however other Offaly fans deliberately exploit this double significance. Flags with [[checkerboard]], repeating stripes, and other patterns are also found.  Flags have been commercially produced which add the county arms to the colours, sometimes augmented with the county name in English or Irish. Such flags have been flown by the [[government of Ireland]] in the Upper Yard at [[Dublin Castle]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hayes |first1=Brian |title=County Flags |url=https://www.oireachtas.ie/en/debates/question/2011-09-14/134/ |website=Parliamentary Questions (31st D\u00e1il) |publisher=Houses of the Oireachtas |accessdate=3 May 2019 |language=en-ie |date=14 September 2011}}</ref> County jerseys formerly often included the county crest, but since the 1980s county boards have developed their own logos; most were originally based on the official county arms, but some have since been replaced with unrelated designs. Flags with these logos added to the county colours are sold by or under licence from the county board.\n\nFans may also wave other flags of the appropriate colours.  For example, among the red-and-white flags used by individual [[Cork GAA|Cork]] supporters have been the [[flag of Canada]] and the [[ensign of the Imperial Japanese Navy]].  As Cork is nicknamed the \"Rebel County\", its fans have also flown the [[Confederate Flag#Confederate flag|Rebel Flag]] of the [[American Civil War]]. Blue-and-gold flags used by [[Tipperary GAA|Tipperary]] supporters have included the national flags [[flag of Sweden|of Sweden]] and [[Flag of Ukraine|of Ukraine]]; Mayo fans have flown the green and red of [[Flag of Italy|Italy]], [[Flag of Portugal|Portugal]] and [[Flag of Bangladesh|Bangladesh]]. [[Kerry GAA|Kerry]] supporters may wave the [[flag of Brazil]] both for its matching colours and to compare [[Kerry GAA honours|Kerry's continual success]] in Gaelic football to the [[Brazil national football team|Brazil national team]]'s in soccer.\n\n==List==\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" \n|+Colours of Irish counties\n!class=\"unsortable\"|Flag !! Province !! County !! Colours !! Notes\n|-\n| [[File:Colours of Antrim.svg|100px|border]] || Ulster|| [[Antrim GAA|Antrim]] || Saffron and White || \n|-\n| [[File:Colours of Armagh.svg|100px|border]] || Ulster|| [[Armagh GAA|Armagh]] || Tangerine and White || \n|-\n| [[File:Colours of Carlow.svg|100px|border]] || Leinster || [[Carlow GAA|Carlow]] || Green, Red and Yellow || \n|-\n| [[File:Colours of Cavan.svg|100px|border]] || Ulster|| [[Cavan GAA|Cavan]] || Blue and White || \n|-\n| [[File:Colours of Clare.svg|100px|border]] || Munster || [[Clare GAA|Clare]] || Saffron and Blue || \n|-\n| [[File:Colours of Cork.svg|100px|border]] || Munster || [[Cork GAA|Cork]] || Red and White || \n|-\n| [[File:Colours of Derry.svg|