s |page=175 |isbn=9781848891777}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[File:Colours of Kildare.svg|100px|border]] || Leinster || [[Kildare GAA|Kildare]] || All White || The kit has black trim, and some fans wave [[chequered flag]]s.\n|-\n| [[File:colours of Kilkenny.svg|100px|border]] || Leinster || [[Kilkenny GAA|Kilkenny]] || Black and Amber || \n|-\n| [[File:Colours of Laois.svg|100px|border]] || Leinster || [[Laois GAA|Laois]] || Blue and White || \n|-\n| [[File:Colours of Leitrim.svg|100px|border]] || Connacht || [[Leitrim GAA|Leitrim]] || Green and Gold || \n|-\n| [[File:Colours of Limerick.svg|100px|border]] || Munster || [[Limerick GAA|Limerick]] || Green and White || \n|-\n| [[File:Colours of Longford.svg|100px|border]] || Leinster || [[Longford GAA|Longford]] || Blue and Gold || \n|-\n| [[File:Colours of Louth.svg|100px|border]] || Leinster || [[Louth GAA|Louth]] || Red and White || \n|-\n| [[File:Colours of Mayo.svg|100px|border]] || Connacht || [[Mayo GAA|Mayo]] || Green and Red || \n|-\n| [[File:Colours of Meath.svg|100px|border]] || Leinster || [[Meath GAA|Meath]] || Green and Yellow || \n|-\n| [[File:Colours of Monaghan.svg|100px|border]] || Ulster|| [[Monaghan GAA|Monaghan]] || White and Blue || \n|-\n| [[File:Colours of Offaly.svg|100px|border]] || Leinster || [[Offaly GAA|Offaly]] || Green, White and Gold || \n|-\n| [[File:Colours of Roscommon.svg|100px|border]] || Connacht || [[Roscommon GAA|Roscommon]] || Primrose and Blue || \n|-\n| [[File:Colours of Sligo.svg|100px|border]] || Connacht || [[Sligo GAA|Sligo]] || Black and White || \n|-\n| [[File:Colours of Tipperary.svg|100px|border]] || Munster || [[Tipperary GAA|Tipperary]] || Blue and Gold || \n|-\n| [[File:Colours of Tyrone.svg|100px|border]] || Ulster|| [[Tyrone GAA|Tyrone]] || White and Red || \n|-\n| [[File:Colours of Waterford.svg|100px|border]] || Munster || [[Waterford GAA|Waterford]] || White and Blue || \n|-\n| [[File:Colours of Westmeath.svg|100px|border]] || Leinster || [[Westmeath GAA|Westmeath]] || Maroon and White || \n|-\n| [[File:Colours of Wexford.svg|100px|border]] || Leinster || [[Wexford GAA|Wexford]] || Purple and Gold || \n|-\n| [[File:Colours of Wicklow.svg|100px|border]] || Leinster || [[Wicklow GAA|Wicklow]] || Blue and Gold || \n|}\n\n==Provinces==\nThe [[GAA Interprovincial Championship]] had a high profile in the mid 20th century. The provincial teams' colours are seldom used as flags in the manner of county colours; instead the pre-existing [[Four Provinces Flag|provincial arms]] are used as [[banner of arms|banner]]s.\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" \n|+Colours of GAA provinces\n! Province !! class=\"unsortable\"|Banner of arms !! colspan=\"2\"| GAA colours \n|- \n| [[Connacht GAA|Connacht]] \n| [[File:Flag of Connacht.svg|100px|border]] \n|data-sort-value=\"White\"          |  \n| White\n|- \n| [[Leinster GAA|Leinster]] \n| [[File:Flag of Leinster.svg|100px|border]] \n|data-sort-value=\"Green and White\"|  [[File:Colours of Leinster Council.svg|100px|border]]\n| Green and White\n|-\n| [[Munster GAA|Munster]]   \n| [[File:Flag of Munster.svg|100px|border]]  \n|data-sort-value=\"Blue and Navy\"  |  [[File:Colours of Munster Council.svg|100px|border]] \n| Blue and Navy\n|- \n| [[Ulster GAA|Ulster]]     \n| [[File:Flag of Ulster.svg|100px|border]]   \n|data-sort-value=\"Gold and Black\" |  \n| Gold and Black\n|}\n\n==Outside Ireland==\nThere are boards for areas of the [[Irish diaspora]] treated as counties within the GAA system. Those in [[Great Britain]] come under the [[British GAA|British Provincial Board]].\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" \n|+Colours of GAA counties outside Ireland\n!class=\"unsortable\"|Flag !! County !! Colours !! Notes\n|-\n| [[File:Colours of Kerry.svg|100px|border]] || [[Gloucestershire GAA|Gloucestershire]] || Gold and Green || \n|-\n| [[File:Colours of Kerry.svg|100px|border]] || [[Hertfordshire GAA|Hertfordshire]] || Green and Yellow || \n|-\n| [[File:Colours of Tipperary.svg|100px|border]] || [[Lancashire GAA|Lancashire]] || Blue and Yellow || \n|-\n| [[File:Colours of Limerick.svg|100px|border]] || [[London GAA|London]] || Green and White || \n|-\n| [[File:Colours of Fingal.svg|100px|border]] || [[Scotland GAA|Scotland]] || Purple and White || \n|-\n| [[File:Colours of Sligo.svg|100px|border]] || [[Warwickshire GAA|Warwickshire]] || Black and White || \n|-\n| [[File:Colours of Cavan.svg|100px|border]]|| [[Yorkshire GAA|Yorkshire]] || Blue and White || \n|-\n| [[File:Colors of New York.svg|100px|border]] || [[New York GAA|New York]] || Red, White and Blue || Covers the [[New York metropolitan area]]. Colours of the [[Flag of New York City]] in reverse order.\n|-\n| [[File:Colours of Laois.svg|100px|border]] || [[North American GAA|North America]] || Red, Blue and White || Country Board of the United States and Canada excluding New York\n|-\n| [[File:Colours of Leitrim.svg|100px|border]]|| [[Australasia GAA|Australasia]] || Green and Gold || Country board of Australia and New Zealand. \n|-\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Irish counties' coats of arms]]. These are the coats of arms of the [[county council]]s; the GAA counties have separate crests, often based on the county council's.\n\n==References==\n===Sources===\n* {{cite web |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140705195711/http://www.gaa.ie/about-the-gaa/provinces-and-counties/about-county/county-colours/ |url=http://www.gaa.ie/about-the-gaa/provinces-and-counties/about-county/county-colours/ |archivedate=5 July 2014 |title=County colours |publisher=GAA }}\n\n===Citations===\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Gaelic Athletic Association}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gaa County Colours}}\n[[Category:Flags of Ireland]]\n[[Category:Gaelic games by county]]\n[[Category:Gaelic games culture|County colours]]\n[[Category:Gaelic games terminology|County colours]]\n[[Category:Lists related to counties of Ireland]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{More citations needed|date=April 2011}}\n[[File:Croke Park fans on the hill.jpg|thumb|right|Fans of [[Tyrone GAA|Tyrone]] (red and white) and [[Meath GAA|Meath]] (green and yellow) on [[Hill 16]] in [[Croke Park]] watching the teams' [[All-Ireland Senior Football Championship 2007#AIQF|2007 All-Ireland football quarterfinal]].]]\nThe '''county colours''' of an [[Counties of Ireland|Irish county]] are the colours of the kit worn by [[GAA county|that county's representative team]] in the inter-county competitions of the [[Gaelic Athletic Association]] (GAA), the most important of which are the [[All-Ireland Senior Football Championship]] and the [[All-Ireland Senior Hurling Championship]].  Fans attending matches often wear replica jerseys, and wave [[flag]]s and [[banner]]s in the county colours.  In the build-up to a major match, flags and [[Bunting (textile)|bunting]] are flown or hung from cars, buildings, telegraph poles, and other fixtures across the county, especially in those regions where GAA support is strong.\n\nWhere a county's jersey is multi-coloured, these are the county colours.  Where the jersey is a single colour, the colour of the shorts is also included.  Shorts were always white until [[Down GAA|Down]] wore black shorts in the [[1968 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship Final|1968 football final]] against [[Kerry GAA|Kerry]], for better contrast in the black-and-white RT\u00c9 telecast.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Keogh |first1=Peter |title=Keogh's Corner: Qualifier draw |url=https://www.pressreader.com/ireland/wicklow-people/20090715/282647503515373 |accessdate=21 August 2019 |work=Wicklow People |via=PressReader.com |date=15 July 2009 |page=62}}</ref> Despite colour telecasts' 1971 arrival,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Boyd |first1=Brian |title=Eurovision in Dublin, 1971: hotpants, 'women\u2019s lib' and boycotts |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/culture/tv-radio-web/eurovision-in-dublin-1971-hotpants-women-s-lib-and-boycotts-1.3491717 |accessdate=21 August 2019 |work=The Irish Times |date=12 May 2018 |language=en}}</ref> other counties switched from white shorts, such as [[Dublin GAA|Dublin]]'s now familiar navy blue.\n\nIn the early years of the All-Ireland championships, each county was formally represented by the club which won its county championship;  players from other clubs within the county were soon added to reinforce the squad, and gradually from 1900 county committees took over the selection of the team. At that date most inter-county teams still wore the kit of the champion club, but by 1910 some counties had adopted a standard strip.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Cronin |first1=Mike |last2=Duncan |first2=Mark |last3=Rouse |first3=Paul |title=The GAA : county by county |date=2011 |publisher=Collins Press |location=Cork |isbn=9781848891289 |pages=6}}</ref> The 1913 [[GAA Congress]] passed a motion proposed by [[P. D. Mehigan]] and seconded by [[Harry Boland]], \"That a distinctive county colour be compulsory for inter-county, inter-provincial and All-Ireland contests, such colours to be approved of by the Provincial Councils concerned and registered with Central Council.\"<ref>{{cite book |last1=Maher |first1=Jim |title=Harry Boland |date=1998 |publisher=Mercier Press |isbn=9781856352369 |page=18 |language=en}}; {{cite web |title=Agenda for 1913 Congress |url=http://www.gaa.ie/centenary/administrative-docs/agenda-f/ |website=Centenary |publisher=GAA |accessdate=9 August 2018 |page=2, Motion 15 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Flags and arms==\n[[File:Dublin Castle Upper Yard county flags.jpg|thumb|Flags with counties' colours and [[List of Irish counties' coats of arms|coats of arms]] flying in the Upper Yard at [[Dublin Castle]]]]\nIn the latter half of the 20th century, the [[county council#Ireland|county council]]s of most counties [[List of Irish counties' coats of arms|designed coats of arms]] for registration with the [[Chief Herald of Ireland]]. Before then, the arms of the [[county town]] often served as arms for the county. The council arms often include the county colours established by the GAA team; examples include [[County Clare|Clare]]<ref>{{cite web |title=What is Clare County Council's Coat of Arms? |url=http://www.clarelibrary.ie/eolas/coclare/history/faqs/council_crest.htm |website=Clare History |publisher=Clare Library |accessdate=14 May 2019}}</ref> and [[County Laois|Laois]].<ref>{{cite web |title=History of the Council \u00bb Coat of Arms |url=https://laois.ie/about-the-council/history-of-the-council/coat-of-arms/ |publisher=Laois County Council |accessdate=14 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nThere are no official county flags; flags with the GAA county colours serve as de facto county flags.  There are no standardised formats for these, except [[Kildare GAA|Kildare]] whose flag, like their kit, is all-white. Typically, flags are formed as vertical bicolours or tricolours, with the major colour nearest the hoist. Horizontal stripes are also found. This is common in [[County Offaly]], where vertical county colours might be mistaken for the [[flag of Ireland]]; however other Offaly fans deliberately exploit this double significance. Flags with [[checkerboard]], repeating stripes, and other patterns are also found.  Flags have been commercially produced which add the county arms to the colours, sometimes augmented with the county name in English or Irish. Such flags have been flown by the [[government of Ireland]] in the Upper Yard at [[Dublin Castle]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hayes |first1=Brian |title=County Flags |url=https://www.oireachtas.ie/en/debates/question/2011-09-14/134/ |website=Parliamentary Questions (31st D\u00e1il) |publisher=Houses of the Oireachtas |accessdate=3 May 2019 |language=en-ie |date=14 September 2011}}</ref> County jerseys formerly often included the county crest, but since the 1980s county boards have developed their own logos; most were originally based on the official county arms, but some have since been replaced with unrelated designs. Flags with these logos added to the county colours are sold by or under licence from the county board.\n\nFans may also wave other flags of the appropriate colours.  For example, among the red-and-white flags used by individual [[Cork GAA|Cork]] supporters have been the [[flag of Canada]] and the [[ensign of the Imperial Japanese Navy]].  As Cork is nicknamed the \"Rebel County\", its fans have also flown the [[Confederate Flag#Confederate flag|Rebel Flag]] of the [[American Civil War]]. Blue-and-gold flags used by [[Tipperary GAA|Tipperary]] supporters have included the national flags [[flag of Sweden|of Sweden]] and [[Flag of Ukraine|of Ukraine]]; Mayo fans have flown the green and red of [[Flag of Italy|Italy]], [[Flag of Portugal|Portugal]] and [[Flag of Bangladesh|Bangladesh]]. [[Kerry GAA|Kerry]] supporters may wave the [[flag of Brazil]] both for its matching colours and to compare [[Kerry GAA honours|Kerry's continual success]] in Gaelic football to the [[Brazil national football team|Brazil national team]]'s in soccer.\n\n==List==\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" \n|+Colours of Irish counties\n!class=\"unsortable\"|Flag !! Province !! County !! Colours !! Notes\n|-\n| [[File:Colours of Antrim.svg|100px|border]] || Ulster|| [[Antrim GAA|Antrim]] || Saffron and White || \n|-\n| [[File:Colours of Armagh.svg|100px|border]] || Ulster|| [[Armagh GAA|Armagh]] || Tangerine and White || \n|-\n| [[File:Colours of Carlow.svg|100px|border]] || Leinster || [[Carlow GAA|Carlow]] || Green, Red and Yellow || \n|-\n| [[File:Colours of Cavan.svg|100px|border]] || Ulster|| [[Cavan GAA|Cavan]] || Blue and White || \n|-\n| [[File:Colours of Clare.svg|100px|border]] || Munster || [[Clare GAA|Clare]] || Saffron and Blue || \n|-\n| [[File:Colours of Cork.svg|100px|border]] || Munster || [[Cork GAA|Cork]] || Red and White || \n|-\n| [[File:Colours of Derry.svg|100px|border]] || Ulster|| [[Derry GAA|Derry]] || Red and White || \n|-\n| [[File:Colours of Donegal.svg|100px|border]] || Ulster|| [[Donegal GAA|Donegal]] || Green and Gold || \n|-\n| [[File:Colours of Down.svg|100px|border]] || Ulster|| [[Down GAA|Down]] || Red and Black || \n|-\n| [[File:Colours of Dublin.svg|100px|border]] || Leinster || [[Dublin GAA|Dublin]] || Navy Blue and Sky Blue || In April 1913, [[Harry Boland]] chaired the Dublin County Board meeting at which \"after some discussion, it was decided to adopt as the county colours a light blue jersey with a white shield bearing the city arms\".<ref>{{cite web |title=1913 Dublin County Board Minutes (Choosing County Colours) |url=https://www.gaa.ie/centenary/illustrative-docs/1913-dub/ |website=Centenary 1913\u20131923 |publisher=GAA |accessdate=3 May 2019 |language=en}}</ref>  \n|-\n| [[File:Colours of Fermanagh.svg|100px|border]] || Ulster|| [[Fermanagh GAA|Fermanagh]] || Green and White || \n|-\n| [[File:Colours of Fingal.svg|100px|border]] || Leinster || [[Fingal GAA|Fingal]] ||Purple and White || [[Fingal]] is not one of the 32 traditional counties of Ireland, but one of four local government areas in the historical area of [[County Dublin]]. Its county hurling team competed separately from Dublin from 2008 to 2016, but its management fell under the Dublin county board.\n|-\n| [[File:Colours of Galway.svg|100px|border]] || Connacht || [[Galway GAA|Galway]] || Maroon and White || \n|-\n| [[File:Colours of Kerry.svg|100px|border]] || Munster || [[Kerry GAA|Kerry]] || Green and Gold \n| Adopted in the [[1903 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship Final|1903 All-Ireland Football Final]] as the colours of the then dominant [[Tralee Mitchels GAA|Tralee Mitchels]] senior team.<ref>{{cite newspaper |title=1903 colours |newspaper=The Kerryman |date=28 January 1961 |page=7}}; {{cite book |last=McElligott |first=Richard |date=2013 |title=Forging a Kingdom: The GAA in Kerry 1884\u20131934 |publisher=Collins Press |page=175 |isbn=9781848891777}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[File:Colours of Kildare.svg|100px|border]] || Leinster || [[Kildare GAA|Kildare]] || All White || The kit has black trim, and some fans wave [[chequered flag]]s.\n|-\n| [[File:colours of Kilkenny.svg|100px|border]] || Leinster || [[Kilkenny GAA|Kilkenny]] || Black and Amber || \n|-\n| [[File:Colours of Laois.svg|100px|border]] || Leinster || [[Laois GAA|Laois]] || Blue and White || \n|-\n| [[File:Colours of Leitrim.svg|100px|border]] || Connacht || [[Leitrim GAA|Leitrim]] || Green and Gold || \n|-\n| [[File:Colours of Limerick.svg|100px|border]] || Munster || [[Limerick GAA|Limerick]] || Green and White || \n|-\n| [[File:Colours of Longford.svg|100px|border]] || Leinster || [[Longford GAA|Longford]] || Blue and Gold || \n|-\n| [[File:Colours of Louth.svg|100px|border]] || Leinster || [[Louth GAA|Louth]] || Red and White || \n|-\n| [[File:Colours of Mayo.svg|100px|border]] || Connacht || [[Mayo GAA|Mayo]] || Green and Red || \n|-\n| [[File:Colours of Meath.svg|100px|border]] || Leinster || [[Meath GAA|Meath]] || Green and Yellow || \n|-\n| [[File:Colours of Monaghan.svg|100px|border]] || Ulster|| [[Monaghan GAA|Monaghan]] || White and Blue || \n|-\n| [[File:Colours of Offaly.svg|100px|border]] || Leinster || [[Offaly GAA|Offaly]] || Green, White and Gold || \n|-\n| [[File:Colours of Roscommon.svg|100px|border]] || Connacht || [[Roscommon GAA|Roscommon]] || Primrose and Blue || \n|-\n| [[File:Colours of Sligo.svg|100px|border]] || Connacht || [[Sligo GAA|Sligo]] || Black and White || \n|-\n| [[File:Colours of Tipperary.svg|100px|border]] || Munster || [[Tipperary GAA|Tipperary]] || Blue and Gold || \n|-\n| [[File:Colours of Tyrone.svg|100px|border]] || Ulster|| [[Tyrone GAA|Tyrone]] || White and Red || \n|-\n| [[File:Colours of Waterford.svg|100px|border]] || Munster || [[Waterford GAA|Waterford]] || White and Blue || \n|-\n| [[File:Colours of Westmeath.svg|100px|border]] || Leinster || [[Westmeath GAA|Westmeath]] || Maroon and White || \n|-\n| [[File:Colours of Wexford.svg|100px|border]] || Leinster || [[Wexford GAA|Wexford]] || Purple and Gold || \n|-\n| [[File:Colours of Wicklow.svg|100px|border]] || Leinster || [[Wicklow GAA|Wicklow]] || Blue and Gold || \n|}\n\n==Provinces==\nThe [[GAA Interprovincial Championship]] had a high profile in the mid 20th century. The provincial teams' colours are seldom used as flags in the manner of county colours; instead the pre-existing [[Four Provinces Flag|provincial arms]] are used as [[banner of arms|banner]]s.\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" \n|+Colours of GAA provinces\n! Province !! class=\"unsortable\"|Banner of arms !! colspan=\"2\"| GAA colours \n|- \n| [[Connacht GAA|Connacht]] \n| [[File:Flag of Connacht.svg|100px|border]] \n|data-sort-value=\"White\"          |  \n| White\n|- \n| [[Leinster GAA|Leinster]] \n| [[File:Flag of Leinster.svg|100px|border]] \n|data-sort-value=\"Green and White\"|  [[File:Colours of Leinster Council.svg|100px|border]]\n| Green and White\n|-\n| [[Munster GAA|Munster]]   \n| [[File:Flag of Munster.svg|100px|border]]  \n|data-sort-value=\"Blue and Navy\"  |  [[File:Colours of Munster Council.svg|100px|border]] \n| Blue and Navy\n|- \n| [[Ulster GAA|Ulster]]     \n| [[File:Flag of Ulster.svg|100px|border]]   \n|data-sort-value=\"Gold and Black\" |  \n| Gold and Black\n|}\n\n==Outside Ireland==\nThere are boards for areas of the [[Irish diaspora]] treated as counties within the GAA system. Those in [[Great Britain]] come under the [[British GAA|British Provincial Board]].\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" \n|+Colours of GAA counties outside Ireland\n!class=\"unsortable\"|Flag !! County !! Colours !! Notes\n|-\n| [[File:Colours of Kerry.svg|100px|border]] || [[Gloucestershire GAA|Gloucestershire]] || Gold and Green || \n|-\n| [[File:Colours of Kerry.svg|100px|border]] || [[Hertfordshire GAA|Hertfordshire]] || Green and Yellow || \n|-\n| [[File:Colours of Tipperary.svg|100px|border]] || [[Lancashire GAA|Lancashire]] || Blue and Yellow || \n|-\n| [[File:Colours of Limerick.svg|100px|border]] || [[London GAA|London]] || Green and White || \n|-\n| [[File:Colours of Fingal.svg|100px|border]] || [[Scotland GAA|Scotland]] || Purple and White || \n|-\n| [[File:Colours of Sligo.svg|100px|border]] || [[Warwickshire GAA|Warwickshire]] || Black and White || \n|-\n| [[File:Colours of Cavan.svg|100px|border]]|| [[Yorkshire GAA|Yorkshire]] || Blue and White || \n|-\n| [[File:Colors of New York.svg|100px|border]] || [[New York GAA|New York]] || Red, White and Blue || Covers the [[New York metropolitan area]]. Colours of the [[Flag of New York City]] in reverse order.\n|-\n| [|| [[North American GAA|North America]] || Red, Blue and White || Country Board of the United States and Canada excluding New York\n|-\n| [[File:Colours of Leitrim.svg|100px|border]]|| [[Australasia GAA|Australasia]] || Green and Gold || Country board of Australia and New Zealand. \n|-\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Irish counties' coats of arms]]. These are the coats of arms of the [[county council]]s; the GAA counties have separate crests, often based on the county council's.\n\n==References==\n===Sources===\n* {{cite web |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140705195711/http://www.gaa.ie/about-the-gaa/provinces-and-counties/about-county/county-colours/ |url=http://www.gaa.ie/about-the-gaa/provinces-and-counties/about-county/county-colours/ |archivedate=5 July 2014 |title=County colours |publisher=GAA }}\n\n===Citations===\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Gaelic Athletic Association}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gaa County Colours}}\n[[Category:Flags of Ireland]]\n[[Category:Gaelic games by county]]\n[[Category:Gaelic games culture|County colours]]\n[[Category:Gaelic games terminology|County colours]]\n[[Category:Lists related to counties of Ireland]]\n", "name_user": "Joelmmh", "label": "safe", "comment": "fixed image link north american gaa", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaelic_games_county_colours"}
{"title_page": "List of active coal-fired power stations in Turkey", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{short description|Coal-fired power stations in the Eurasian country}}\n[[File:Yenik\u00f6y Power Plant Milas Mu\u011fla Turkey.jpg|thumb|[[Yenik\u00f6y power station|Yenik\u00f6y]] (pictured), [[Yata\u011fan power station|Yata\u011fan]] and [[Kemerk\u00f6y power station|Kemerk\u00f6y]] have made [[Mu\u011fla]] a [[sulfur dioxide]] hotspot of [[air pollution in Turkey]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://storage.googleapis.com/planet4-international-stateless/2019/08/e40af3dd-global-hotspot-and-emission-sources-for-so2_16_august-2019.pdf|title=Global SO2 emission hotspot database: Ranking the world\u2019s worst sources of SO2 pollution|last=Dahiya|first=Sunil|last2=Myllyvirta|first2=Lauri|publisher=[[Greenpeace]]|year=2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://anterhaber.com/mucep-mugla-daki-tum-santreller-kapatilsin/4901/|title=MU\u00c7EP \u201cMu\u011fla\u2019daki t\u00fcm santreller kapat\u0131ls\u0131n\u201d|last=|first=|date=|website=Anter Haber|language=tr|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=4 January 2020}}</ref>]]\n{{As of|2020}}, of the 52 coal-fired [[List of power stations in Turkey|power stations in Turkey]], 47 are currently generating electricity,<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.dailysabah.com/turkey/2020/01/01/5-power-plants-shut-in-turkey-for-not-completing-environment-protocols|title=5 power plants shut in Turkey for not completing environment protocols|date=January 1, 2020|publisher=[[Daily Sabah]]}}</ref> with a total capacity of about 17 [[gigawatt|gigawatts (GW)]].{{refn|group=note|The [[Ministry of Energy and Natural Resources (Turkey)|Energy Ministry]] gives a figure of 67 power stations, but does not list them<ref name=MENR>{{Cite web|url=http://www.enerji.gov.tr/en-US/Pages/Electricity|title=Republic of Turkey Ministry of Energy and Natural Resources - Electricity|website=enerji.gov.tr|access-date=2020-02-14}}</ref> and the Energy Market Regulatory Authority database lists 52.}} In 2018 [[coal-fired power station]]s generated 113 [[TWh|terawatt hours (TWh)]], which was 37% of [[electricity sector in Turkey|the nation's electricity]].<ref name=\"MinEn\">{{cite web |title=Coal |url=http://www.enerji.gov.tr/en-US/Pages/Coal |publisher=[[Ministry of Energy and Natural Resources (Turkey)]] |accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Lignite|Lignite (brown coal)]] is mined locally, whereas almost all hardcoal for power stations is imported; 69 and 22 million tonnes respectively in 2019.<ref name=\"E\u00dcA\u015e2018report\">{{cite book |title=2018 Annual Report |publisher=[[E\u00dcA\u015e]] |page=20 |url=https://api.euas.gov.tr/file/6bbe8457-5164-42ff-9317-0a90ef33f55f?download}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gercekgundem.com/cevre/159797/tuik-termik-santrallere-2019da-91-milyon-ton-komur-verildi|title=T\u00dc\u0130K: Termik santrallere 2019'da 91 milyon ton k\u00f6m\u00fcr verildi|website=www.gercekgundem.com|language=tr|access-date=2020-03-05}}</ref> Both types of coal emit over 1&nbsp;kg of [[carbon dioxide]] for every [[kilowatt hour]] generated,<ref>Atilgan et al (2016), p. 177</ref> over twice that of a [[gas-fired power station]], so coal-fired power stations are the largest contributor to [[greenhouse gas emissions by Turkey]].{{refn|group=note|UNFCCC category 1.A.1. Energy industries a. Public electricity and heat production:solid fuels. Cell G26 on table 1.A(a)s1 shows 111 megatonnes of CO2, which is larger than any other category.{{cite web|work=Turkish Statistical Institute|title=Turkish Greenhouse Gas Inventory 1990 - 2018 common reporting format (CRF) tables [TurkStat tables]|date=April 2020|url=https://unfccc.int/sites/default/files/resource/tur-2020-crf-13apr20.zip|format=TUR_2020_2018_13042020_112534.xlsx}}}}\n\nTo minimize transport costs, power stations burning imported coal are usually located on the coast: there are clusters in [[\u00c7anakkale Province|\u00c7anakkale]] and [[Zonguldak Province|Zonguldak]] provinces and around [[Iskenderun Bay]], and 31.7 million tonnes of thermal coal was imported in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.montelnews.com/en/story/turkish-coal-imports-set-to-rise-in-2020--analysts/1086380|title=Turkish coal imports set to rise in 2020 \u2013 analysts|website=www.montelnews.com|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref>  However those burning lignite tend to be near [[:Category:Coal mines in Turkey|local coalmines]], such as [[Elbistan coalfield|Elbistan]], because [[Coal_in_Turkey#Lignite|Turkish lignite]] is very low quality so not worth transporting. Lignite burning power stations have [[Dispatchable generation|priority over other types of generation]]<ref>{{Cite book|last=Turhan|first=Ethemcan|url=https://www.oapen.org/download?type=document&docid=1005506|title=Transforming Socio-Natures in Turkey: Landscapes, State and Environmental Movements|last2=\u00d6zkaynak|first2=Beg\u00fcm|last3=Ayd\u0131n|first3=Cem \u0130skender|publisher=|year=2020|isbn=978-0-429-42969-9|location=|pages=179}}</ref> and in 2019 [[List of power stations in Turkey#Coal|large lignite burning stations were subsidized]] with [[Electricity market#Capacity market|capacity payments]] totalling almost 1 billion [[Turkish lira|lira]] (almost 150 million USD).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.enerjigunlugu.net/2019da-40-santrale-1-6-milyar-lira-destek-35998h.htm|title=Kapasite mekanizmas\u0131yla 2019\u2019da 40 santrale 1.6 milyar lira \u00f6dendi|date=2020-02-06|website=Enerji G\u00fcnl\u00fc\u011f\u00fc|language=tr|access-date=2020-02-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.milasonder.com/gundem/mucep-mugladaki-tum-termik-santraller-kapatilmalidir/48728|title=MU\u00c7EP: Mu\u011fla\u2019daki t\u00fcm termik santraller kapatilmalidir!|website=www.milasonder.com|language=tr|access-date=2020-02-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200204180955/https://www.milasonder.com/gundem/mucep-mugladaki-tum-termik-santraller-kapatilmalidir/48728|archive-date=4 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAlthough five old power stations ([[Af\u015fin-Elbistan power stations|Af\u015fin-Elbistan A]], [[Seyit\u00f6mer power station|Seyit\u00f6mer]], Tun\u00e7bilek, [[Kangal power station|Kangal]] and  \u00c7atala\u011fz\u0131) were shut down at the end of 2019 and are not being restarted unless and until they meet new pollution limits,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/energy/coal/turkey-shuts-power-plants-for-not-installing-filters/27934|title=Turkey shuts power plants for not installing filters|publisher=[[Anadolu Agency]]|date=2 January 2020|access-date=2 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200102173027/https://www.aa.com.tr/en/energy/coal/turkey-shuts-power-plants-for-not-installing-filters/27934|archive-date=2 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and despite abundant [[renewable energy in Turkey|sun and wind]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.enerji.gov.tr/en-US/Pages/Wind|title=Republic of Turkey Ministry of Energy and Natural Resources - Wind|website=enerji.gov.tr|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> [[Emba Hunutlu power station|Emba Hunutlu]] is under construction.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2019-09/23/c_138413218.htm|title=China's power plant project with direct investment in Turkey starts construction - Xinhua {{!}} English.news.cn|website=www.xinhuanet.com|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> Unlike neighbouring Greece, which is closing down all its lignite-fired power stations,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ekathimerini.com/249652/article/ekathimerini/business/lignite-phase-out-a-key-aspect-of-national-energy-policy-mitsotakis-says|title=Lignite phase-out a key aspect of national energy policy, Mitsotakis says {{!}} Kathimerini|website=www.ekathimerini.com|language=English|access-date=2020-02-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200221141841/http://www.ekathimerini.com/249652/article/ekathimerini/business/lignite-phase-out-a-key-aspect-of-national-energy-policy-mitsotakis-says|archive-date=21 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Turkey has approved building<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.enerjigunlugu.net/euas-1800-mwlik-afsin-c-termik-santrali-icin-calismalara-basliyor-36266h.htm|title=E\u00dcA\u015e 1800 MW\u2019l\u0131k Af\u015fin C Termik Santrali i\u00e7in \u00e7al\u0131\u015fmalara ba\u015fl\u0131yor|date=2020-02-27|website=Enerji G\u00fcnl\u00fc\u011f\u00fc|language=tr|access-date=2020-03-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302193622/https://www.enerjigunlugu.net/euas-1800-mwlik-afsin-c-termik-santrali-icin-calismalara-basliyor-36266h.htm|archive-date=2 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Af\u015fin-Elbistan C power station|Af\u015fin-Elbistan C]]. The [[Turkey Wealth Fund]], the country's [[sovereign wealth fund]], is financing it because the country needs to maintain energy security by reducing fossil fuel imports.<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailysabah.com/economy/2020/01/21/turkey-wealth-fund-eyes-becoming-strategic-investment-arm-of-the-country|title=Turkey Wealth Fund eyes becoming strategic investment arm of the country|last=\u00d6zt\u00fcrk|first=Sinan|date=2020-01-21|website=Daily Sabah|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> The fund aims to pay dividends to the government,<ref name=\"TWF\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.dailysabah.com/economy/2020/01/21/turkey-wealth-fund-eyes-becoming-strategic-investment-arm-of-the-country|title=Turkey Wealth Fund eyes becoming strategic investment arm of the country|last=\u00d6zt\u00fcrk|first=Sinan|date=2020-01-21|work=[[Daily Sabah]]}}</ref> but according to [[Carbon Tracker]], a [[think tank]], new coal power will lose money.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/energy-and-environment/2020/3/14/21177941/climate-change-coal-renewable-energy|title=4 astonishing signs of coal\u2019s declining economic viability|last=Roberts|first=David|date=2020-03-14|website=Vox|language=en|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref> \n\nThe main opposition [[Republican People's Party (Turkey)|Republican People's Party]] claims temporary licenses for the first half of 2020 for five older power stations which exceed [[sulfur dioxide]] pollution limits are illegal.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.kamuguncelhaber.com/kapanan-santrallere-devlet-destegi-devam-edecek.html|title=Kapanan santrallere devlet deste\u011fi devam edecek|date=2020-01-29|publisher=Kamu G\u00fcncel Haber|language=tr|access-date=4 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200204195552/https://www.kamuguncelhaber.com/kapanan-santrallere-devlet-destegi-devam-edecek.html|archive-date=4 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>  {{As of|2020}} the results of 2019 pollution control inspections by the [[Ministry of Environment and Urban Planning (Turkey)|Environment Ministry]] have not been made public<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sivilsayfalar.org/2020/02/03/polluted-air-takes-more-lives-than-traffic-accidents/|title=Polluted Air Takes More Lives Than Traffic Accidents|date=2020-02-03|website=Sivil Sayfalar|access-date=2020-02-10}}</ref> and (unlike the EU) neither are the [[smokestack]] or lignite [[Heat of combustion|net calorific value]] measurements from each station: so public information on the carbon-dioxide emissions of individual power stations may not be available until after [[Sentinel-7]] satellites measure them directly from 2025.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.euractiv.com/section/outer-space/news/co2-tracking-satellites-crucial-for-climate-efforts-say-space-experts/|title=CO2-tracking satellites crucial for climate efforts, say space experts|last=Morgan|first=Sam|date=2019-12-05|website=www.euractiv.com|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200201072857/https://www.euractiv.com/section/outer-space/news/co2-tracking-satellites-crucial-for-climate-efforts-say-space-experts/|archive-date=1 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Much of the operational fleet was built in the 21st century:  however the oversupply of generating capacity and 2020 drop in demand may create financial problems for power station operators,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dailysabah.com/business/energy/turkeys-electricity-demand-falls-as-coronavirus-constricts-economic-activity|title=Turkey\u2019s electricity demand falls as coronavirus constricts economic activity|publisher=[[Daily Sabah]]|date=2020-03-31}}</ref> as a  quarter of power stations are estimated to be [[Cash flow|cashflow]] negative.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://carbontracker.org/reports/political-decisions-economic-realities/|title=Political decisions, economic realities: The underlying operating cashflows of coal power during COVID-19|website=Carbon Tracker Initiative|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> Moreover the price of natural gas fell in 2020,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oxfordenergy.org/wpcms/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/2-gas-in-Europe-is-here-who-will-blink-first.pdf|title=$2 gas in Europe is here: who will blink first?|last=Fulwood|first=Mike|date=March 2020|website=Oxford Institute for Energy Studies|url-status=live}}</ref> making Turkey's already existing gas-fired power stations more competitive,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hellenicshippingnews.com/commodities-2020-turkish-gas-market-promising-further-changes-in-2020/|title=Commodities 2020: Turkish gas market promising further changes in 2020|publisher=Hellenic Shipping News|date=3 January 2020|access-date=3 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200103095415/https://www.hellenicshippingnews.com/commodities-2020-turkish-gas-market-promising-further-changes-in-2020/|archive-date=3 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> so new coal-fired power stations may not in fact be completed<ref name=\":3\" /> due to the risk of becoming [[stranded asset]]s.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.climate-transparency.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/05/Managing-the-phase-out-of-coal-DIGITAL.pdf|title=Managing the phase-out of coal: A comparison of actions in G20 countries|last=|first=|publisher=[[Climate Transparency]]|year=2019|isbn=|location=|pages=|access-date=3 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190524071757/https://www.climate-transparency.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/05/Managing-the-phase-out-of-coal-DIGITAL.pdf|archive-date=24 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>{{Location map+\n | Turkey\n | width          = 1000\n | float          = center\n | border         =\n | caption        = Location of operational and under construction coal-fired power stations larger than 50 megawatts in Turkey (yellow dot means uncertain or not fully operational)\n | alt            =\n | relief         = yes\n | AlternativeMap =\n | overlay_image  =\n | places         =\n \n{{ Location map~\n  | Turkey\n  | label      = <small>[[Af\u015fin-Elbistan B power station|Af\u015fin-ElbistanB]]</small>\n  | label_size =\n  | position   = top\n  | background = #FEFEE9\n  | mark       = \n  | marksize   = 16\n  | link       =\n  | lat_deg    = 38.4\n  | lon_deg    = 36.98\n }}\n{{ Location map~\n  | Turkey\n  | label      = <small>[[Atlas Enerji \u0130skenderun power station|Atlas Enerji \u0130skenderun]]</small>\n  | label_size =\n  | position   = below\n  | background = #FEFEE9\n  | mark       = \n  | marksize   = 16\n  | link       =\n  | lat_deg    = 36.69028\n  | lon_deg    = 36.20909\n }}\n{{ Location map~\n  | Turkey\n  | label      = <small>Bolu G\u00f6yn\u00fck</small>\n  | label_size =\n  | position   = left\n  | background = #FEFEE9\n  | mark       = \n  | marksize   =\n  | link       =\n  | lat_deg    = 40.2514\n  | lon_deg    = 30.8129\n }}\n{{ Location map~\n  | Turkey\n  | label      = <small>Cenal</small>\n  | label_size =\n  | position   = right\n  | background = #FEFEE9\n  | mark       = \n  | marksize   = 16\n  | link       =\n  | lat_deg    = 40.4167\n  | lon_deg    = 27.31829\n }}\n{{ Location map~\n  | Turkey\n  | label      = <small>[[Gebze \u00c7olako\u011flu power station|G